Who is the fastest and most reliable node provider out there now? Can't build our way out of the bear market if RPC calls are taking 800ms to complete

Maybe it's time for a node benchmarking tool.. something like siege or ab but for blockchain nodes.

Thinking about making a tool to benchmark blockchain node and IPFS providers. Does this exist yet? And which benchmarks would you want to see?
Multicall as in you're hitting the multicall contract once with a huge payload, or batching RPC calls in a single network call?

And agree, this should be totally reasonable. 

Basically we're just reading data from disk and most of it is data that does not change. 

https://static.googleusercontent.com/media/sre.google/en//static/pdf/rule-of-thumb-latency-numbers-letter.pdf https://i.imgur.com/k0cVfKm.png
Makes sense. Definitely are pros and cons to each -- multiple RPC calls batched into a single network request = very easy to parallelize. And multicall = when it works it's such a huge time saver.
it's kind of surprising that we haven't had much innovation as far as it comes to blockchain nodes. Imagine if we had /dev/ethereum
genuinely curiously asking: how do you make it decentralized and fast and reliable at the same time? Do you have a benchmark or a script someone can run to actually see for themselves?

(1/2) Something really cool we do for our new services:

We have a simple but powerful observability framework that makes it really easy to 1) say what you want to instrument and measure, and to 2) make sure you're calling it correctly. https://i.imgur.com/NAgb7vs.png

There's nothing worse than realizing you called it the wrong thing and now your statsd has event-name and EVENT_NAME. With this, event types and timers are strongly typed and defined. https://i.imgur.com/Q7YVD7w.png

Metrics and observability (o11y) are actually pretty easy to set up but so easy to break, sometimes silently. 

And 2 years in nobody is comfortable touching the "critical_path.timer" that someone wrote a long time ago, so metrics and data just build and become less valuable.
We can build an API for this.
